  <scaffolding>
    <layer level="1" name="Layer 1">
      <focus/>
      <content>Core definitions: Contractual liability risk (legal/financial repercussions from failing cybersecurity contract obligations); Cybersecurity obligations (data protection, incident response, access controls); Breach of contract (failure to meet clauses, e.g., data breach); Risk (potential loss from incidents breaching contracts). Concept map central node: 'Contractual Liability Risk' → 'Cybersecurity Obligations' → 'Breach of Contract' → 'Legal/Financial Repercussions'.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>Relationships: Obligations → Breaches (e.g., non-compliance with standards) → Repercussions (lawsuits, fines). Key frameworks: NIST SP 800-161r1 (Cybersecurity Supply Chain Risk Management - C-SCRM practices for identifying/assessing supply chain risks); NIST CSF 2.0 GOVERN (GV) function (GV.OC Organizational Context, GV.RM Risk Management Strategy, GV.RR Roles/Responsibilities, GV.PO Policy, GV.OV Oversight - emphasizes governance for supply chain and contractual risks).</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Step-by-step processes: 1) Contract review checklist (security clauses, SLAs, indemnity); 2) Risk assessment (map to NIST SP 800-161); 3) Mitigation strategies (audit rights, right-to-audit, termination clauses); 4) Incident response integration.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Broader links: NIST CSF 2.0 full integration (GOVERN oversees Identify.Supply Chain Risk Management - ID.SC); Supply chain risks (vendor ecosystems); Real cases (SolarWinds, Equifax contractual fallout). Sources: NIST CSF 2.0 (https://doi.org/10.6028/NIST.CSWP.29); NIST SP 800-161r1 (https://doi.org/10.6028/NIST.SP.800-161r1).</content>
    </layer>
  </scaffolding>
